english:
  title: The Eastern River
  author: Park Eun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A thousand miles to keep our promise of simple millet and wine,
    Through the night I hear again the voice of wind and rain.
    These mountains and rivers, by chance falling into my hands a hundred years hence—
    What gain or loss could ever move my heart?

    Gathering and parting drift like clouds that come and go,
    Life and death flicker like a lamp extinguished and lit.
    I happen upon this meaning and cannot help but laugh:
    This body is not bronze or stone, holding fast forever.

    I forced this body into endless toil,
    Chasing carriages and high position, seeking fame and rank.
    It is no different from a tree that wishes to become lumber,
    Not knowing it shall end up burned and broken.

    I have seen the parasol tree, finest of all timber—
    Yet daily on the mountain, axe and hatchet contest for it.
    Even as a musical instrument it cannot endure,
    Sometimes split into kindling, singing in the fire.

    In ancient times, precious tortoise shells were wrapped in silk,
    Yet they could not drag their tails through the mud and live.

    When we first kept company as beardless youths,
    We wandered barefoot through neighboring villages.
    We knew neither sorrow nor joy, just endless peace—
    The ten thousand things before our eyes, yet we saw nothing.

    That innocence has been carved away, and here we are,
    Having learned to bow and scrape, to bear the weight of the world.
    Threatened by calamity, tempted by glory,
    I became a creature of fear—head heavy with dread, tail trembling.

    The thick earth seemed ready to swallow me,
    The high heaven appeared about to topple.
    For ten long years I stumbled toward the pit,
    Again and again nearly falling in.

    Like one who recalls the pain after illness,
    I wake as from a dream, my heart startled.

    But recently heaven has loosened its bridle—
    This old man escapes both mockery and judgment.
    You too have found leisure in a minor post,
    And come to dwell in simple repose, tending your mother.

    We meet again after years apart,
    Our many promises now finally kept.

    This morning we climbed the Phoenix Rock,
    Where ten thousand vistas pressed forward to greet us.
    Sea clouds drew back the sun like opening a mirror-case,
    And heaven's wind shook the valley into song.

    Thousand-layered azaleas painted the mountains like art,
    Ten miles of waves bore our sail forward.
    We drank deeply, sparing nothing,
    And lay among the rocks with wine for our pillow.

    Sea gulls came close, unafraid to draw near,
    Old countrymen gathered round, taking their places beside us.

    From this day forward let us ride a small boat together,
    And cast ourselves adrift as companions through winter's years.
    My body has already shed the dust of worldly entanglement—
    Why should I wash my cap-strings in the running stream?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'promise of millet and wine' refers to the ancient Chinese story of a gentleman farmer who invited a friend to visit him. The phrase suggests a simple reunion between old friends.
  - key: ''
    value: Phoenix Rock (鳳凰岩) and the Eastern River (東江) are landmarks in Korea, suggesting the poet is traveling with a companion to visit a cherished location.
  - key: ''
    value: The parasol tree (梧桐) was a classical symbol of excellence but also of misfortune—fine materials were often cut down for use. The poet uses it as a meditation on fate.
  - key: ''
    value: The final image of not washing the cap-strings expresses complete detachment from worldly concerns and social position.
